{
  "explanation": "While embezzling $25,000 from an employer constitutes a significant breach of trust and a serious financial crime, the court must weigh both the aggravating and mitigating factors. The defendant has no prior criminal record, which indicates this is an isolated incident rather than a pattern of criminal behavior. Furthermore, the defendant has already made partial restitution, showing remorse and a good-faith effort to make the victim whole. The courtroom disruption by a spectator demanding a 10-year sentence is entirely irrelevant to the legal standards of sentencing and is completely disregarded. A 12-month period of incarceration, followed by probation and a mandate to complete the remaining restitution, is an appropriate and proportionate consequence that balances accountability with the potential for rehabilitation.",
  "verdict": 12
}
